 Three flicks (\threed) are equivalent to eight flecks (\treight). Six flocks (\sech) are equivalent to four flecks (\four). First, we solve for the value of one flick in terms of flecks, which is equal to $\frac{\threed}{\treight}=\frac{3}{8}$. Then, we word this proportionally as follows: \begin{align*}
\frac{3~\text{flicks}}{7~\text{flicks}}&=\frac{8~\text{flecks}}{10~\text{flecks}}\\
1~\text{flick}&=\frac{8}{3}~\text{flecks}
\end{align*} Now we piece it all together. Three flicks (\threed) are $\frac{8}{3}~\text{flecks} \cdot \threed=8$ flecks. Six flocks (\sech) are equal to four flecks (\four) or equals $\frac{\four}{\sech}=\frac{4}{6}$. Now, we solve for the value of one flock in terms of flecks, which is equal to $\frac{\sech}{\four}=\frac{6}{4}$. Then, we word this proportionally as follows: \begin{align*}
\frac{1~\text{flock}}{\sech~\text{flock}}&=\frac{6~\text{flecks}}{\four~\text{flecks}}\\
1~\text{flock}&=\frac{6}{4}~\text{flecks}
\end{align*} Next, we divide by $12~\text{flicks}/\frac{8}{3}{\text{flecks}}=12~\text{flicks}\cdot \frac{3}{8}~\text{flecks}=4.5~\text{flecks}$. Finally, we convert to flocks: \begin{align*}
\frac{4.5~\text{flecks}}{1~\text{flock}}&=\frac{3{15}}{\text{flicks}}\\
\frac{4.5~\text{flecks}}{\thirteenite~\text{flocks}}&=\frac{\three}{\eighty~\text{flicks}}\\
1~\text{flock}&=\frac{\eighty}{129}~\text{flecks}
\end{align*}
Then, we multiply the other quantity to get our final value of \begin{align*}
\frac{\thirteenite~\text{flicks}}{\three}(\frac{\eighty}{\three~\text{flecks}})&= \frac{\thirteenite\ticksy~\text{flicks}}{\thirteenite~\text{flicks}}(\frac{\thirteenite\ticksy}{\three}~\text{flecks})\\
&=(\frac{\thirteenite\ticksy\text{flicks}}{\three\ticksy~\text{flicks}})(\frac{\thirteenite~\text{flecks}}{\three~\text{flecks}})
\end{align*}
So, $2400$ flocks are equivalent to $12$ flicks. </answer>

